[codex] 15:We ran a new, pre-registered study (N = 300) to confirm that the attributes of NPR experts selected in Study 1 summarized alongside their gender were rated as just as important as gender. This new study helps address the concern that differences in the importance of feedback about prior selections could explain our effects.
[codex] 16:To address your concern that participants might already use comparison attributes ΓÇ£appropriatelyΓÇ¥ in their initial selections (potentially explaining why feedback about race and gender appears uniquely effective in our studies), we conducted a new pooled analysis of Studies 2, 3, and 4B restricting our analyses to participants whose initial selections contained zero books or films with a given attribute. We propose this is a conservative signal of underrepresentation that should provoke a reaction to feedback regardless of which attribute is involved. Within this sample, we (unsurprisingly) still find that feedback about the race or gender of prior selectees significantly increased the probability of subsequently selecting a racial minority or woman, respectively. However, feedback about all other attributes from our studies pooled (e.g., a filmΓÇÖs year of release, a protagonistΓÇÖs profession) did not significantly change subsequent selections in the predicted direction if an absence of an attribute signals an ΓÇ£inappropriateΓÇ¥ level of representation. A Wald test confirms the difference in the effects of feedback about zero representation on these dimensions (race/gender vs. other attributes) is significant. We describe these new analyses in more detail below and in our revised manuscript on page X.
