[codex] 37:We have also sought to clarify the high-level conditions under which we expect our theory to hold. In the revised manuscript, we acknowledge that firmsΓÇÖ pullbacks from explicit DEI commitments may reduce one source of external pressure on decision-makers to avoid patterns of selections that might be judged as signaling prejudice. At the same time, we explain how organizational commitments are not the only reason people would be expected to care about feedback on the low rates of race/gender diversity in  their past selectees. Anti-discrimination law, the visibility of selection decisions, employee and stakeholder expectations, broader reputational concerns, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments should all continue to make race and gender consequential in selection contexts even if a specific employer is not supportive of DEI policies. We now state more clearly that descriptive feedback should be most likely to matter when past selection patterns could raise concerns about prejudice, and less likely to matter in environments where those concerns are less likely to arise. Given your note that an additional study is not required, in order to be maximally responsive to your earlier comment about streamlining the manuscript, we address this issue through writing. Our point-by-point reply to Reviewer 2 (Page X of this response letter) dives into this more deeply, and our General Discussion now identifies exploring whether organizational DEI climate may moderate the effect of feedback about race/gender on subsequent selection decisions as a valuable direction for future research.
[codex] 38:I have two remaining requests, one about style and one about analysis.  Although the paper is generally well-written and the studies are well-designed, I found reading the paper a bit of a slog.  Some of that is that much of the analysis was nearly identical across studies, and the repetitive style of reporting made the paper feel bulky.  I understand that my tastes for writing and streamlining might be idiosyncratic, but I wonder if there can be streamlining (as in Figure 2) in which some of the repeated analysis (like comparison between the theoretically targeted feedback and the ΓÇ£controlΓÇ¥ feedback) shows up in a Table with the relevant statistics.  I wonΓÇÖt make this a requirement, but IΓÇÖd like the authors to take this feedback (no pun intended) seriously and consider whether there is something that can be done.  I will also add that the paper right now is close to the page limit since you have moved the figures and tables out of the main text (ΓÇ£All invited revisions must adhere to the following page limit: 47 pages with 25 lines of text per page (double spacing) or 32 pages with 33 lines of text per page (1.5 spacing). An online appendix will not count toward the page limit.ΓÇ¥ https://pubsonline.informs.org/page/mnsc/submission-guidelines)
[codex] 39:RESPONSE: We thank you for this feedback and agree that the prior versionΓÇÖs repeated presentation of the same comparisons made the empirical sections longer than warranted. The revised manuscript is now [X] pages and reflects a substantial streamlining of the Methods and Results sections, particularly for later studies to avoid unnecessary repetition/redundancy. To that end, and following your guidance, we have relegated the reporting of the regression specifications behind the secondary feedback-about-race/gender-versus-other-attribute comparisons to a dedicated section of the Appendix, with explicit references from the later Results sections. 
[codex] 40:I think that Study 4b goes a long way in terms of convincing me that there is something special about gender/racial etc representational feedback relative to feedback on other attributes.  One though and one request.  Although I think that the package of studies is very compelling, I still found myself wishing that you had tested whether the alternative descriptive feedback that you shared was on par with gender in terms of importance.  My intuition, for example, in Study 1 is that ΓÇ£(1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a universityΓÇ¥ would be seen as less important than gender.  Two suggestions -- you could get a separate group and ΓÇ£post-testΓÇ¥ some of these items and if they are as important or nearly as important report that.  If on the other hand, they are a lot less important, I would ask you to consider running Study 1 again so that the paper starts with a strong study.
[codex] 41:RESPONSE: Thank you for this suggestion. We ran the post-test you proposed and have incorporated the results into the Methods section of Study 1 (p. X). In a new pre-registered study (https://aspredicted.org/xa7u94.pdf), we recruited 300 Prolific participants and randomly assigned each to rate the importance of one of the four attributes featured in Study 1 (how many of the selected experts were women, worked at a university, were under 50 years old, or were based on the West Coast of the United States) for selecting NPR experts on a scale from 1 = ΓÇ£Not at all importantΓÇ¥ to 7 = ΓÇ£Very important.ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£Worked at a universityΓÇ¥ was rated as significantly more important than gender (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥: M = 3.87, SD = 1.92; ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥: M = 4.50, SD = 1.48; t(139.0) = 2.26, p = .026, d = 0.37). ΓÇ£Were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ did not differ significantly from gender in rated importance (M = 4.05, SD = 1.74; t(146.6) = 0.62, p = .534, d = 0.10). ΓÇ£Were based on the West Coast of the United StatesΓÇ¥ was rated as less important than gender (M = 3.11, SD = 1.81; t(146.7) = 2.48, p = .014, d = 0.41). Two of the three comparison attributes were thus rated as at least as important as gender. These results suggest that differences in the perceived importance of the type of feedback participants receive about their selections in Study 1 are unlikely to account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections.
[codex] 42:On the request, I liked Study 4b and think that it does a good job of showing that feedback about gender is different than feedback about other important dimensions.  In addition, your studies show that gender/race feedback lead subjects to adjust their portfolios about the base rate.  That said, IΓÇÖm still left wondering whether your findings are showing what you say or it is just that people use these other measures appropriately in their initial selections.  IΓÇÖd like you to at least discuss this possibility, and perhaps there is additional analysis that you can do to address this.
[codex] 43:RESPONSE: Thank you for raising this possibility. We now both discuss it (see p. X) and a follow-up analysis that attempts to address this point. 
[codex] 44:We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback suggesting that women and minorities have been vastly underrepresented in their past selections compared to the U.S. population. If underrepresentation of any group is responsible for our effects, then if the descriptive feedback we provided on some other selection attribute (say, the age of prior selectees) suggested a massive underrepresentation (say, of people over 50), this might drive a similar reaction. We conducted an additional analysis to try to address this possibility. Assuming that selecting zero options with a given attribute would always signal underrepresentation, we test the hypothesis that feedback shifts in who is subsequently selected to make up for underrepresentation not just when it comes to race and gender but on any dimension. To examine this hypothesis, we pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (clustering standard errors by participant). We only retain observations involving participants who made an initial set of selections that included zero books or movies with a given attribute (e.g., a set of films in Study 3A that included zero films released after 2010, or a set of books in Study 4B that included zero books with women authors). We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, across these studies, receiving this feedback (that they had selected no women or racial minorities) significantly increases the probability of selecting a racial minority or woman as their final selection, respectively, by 22.50 percentage points (p < .001, N = 864). Among participants who initially selected zero movies, books, or authors with any of the other attributes under study (e.g., budget, year of release, or protagonistΓÇÖs profession), feedback informing them that none of their selectees had those other attributes did not significantly alter their probability of subsequently selecting an additional movie, book, or author with the relevant attribute (b = 7.25 percentage points; p = .19, N = 414). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients confirms that the pooled effect of feedback on subsequent choices is significantly larger when feedback is about the race or gender of initial selections than when it is about other features of initial selections (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.87, +27.63]). We have added a footnote to the General Discussion (p. X), anchored on the sentence where we first state the differential effect of race or gender feedback versus comparison-attribute feedback. The footnote summarizes the cross-study rule-out and points readers to Appendix Section S[X] for the full per-cell analysis. We hope these additional analyses sufficiently address your comment.
