[codex] 51:Reviewer: 1
[codex] 52:Comments:
[codex] 53:-IΓÇÖm always pleased when a research team takes feedback from reviews seriously, conducts more experiments to resolve some questions and is more circumspect about their conclusions: all of that seems to be true here.
[codex] 54:I really like the two studies that were added to the paper (particularly the library reading list study as I thought this was a bigger issue of the last submission). I also think it is nice that they provide data to show the ΓÇ£reverseΓÇ¥ discrimination effects here. I think they now have clear evidence for both the motive to reduce prejudice and the additional motive of wanting to treat others the same.
[codex] 55:They also include more relevant JDM literature here to further clarify the importance of their point of their findingsΓÇöboth being more circumspect about their scope and detailing precisely what they found.
[codex] 56:RESPONSE: Thank you for your kind words about our revision and for the careful guidance you have provided on how to improve our paper.
[codex] 57:-Small things to think about for revision:
[codex] 58:For the point about explicit goals being necessarily you cite some older stuff (e.g., Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al.,2007), any updated cites you can chuck in? Just makes it clearer how this is fitting in with contemporary literature in this area given that this is the first implication you discuss and the bigger one, IΓÇÖd like to see a bit more there.
[codex] 59:RESPONSE: Thank you for this helpful suggestion. We have updated our citations so we now cite Locke and Latham (2019) alongside the classic Locke and Latham (2002) as well as Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018) alongside the classic Schultz et al. (2007). These new citations reference contemporary updates to two foundational pieces we previously cited.
[codex] 60:This could be added to the intro as well, there the most recent paper is from like 2016 and that is just showing that the pairing works, not that the pairing in necessary. Not required, but might be helpful to beef that up as it is the primary obligation. Also, you could discuss if you think this happens here because that other goal is emphasized enough to people. Expanding a bit more on the theory there might be helpful for the theory piece.
[codex] 61:RESPONSE: Thank you for pressing us on this point. We have refreshed the introductionΓÇÖs feedback and goals citations to draw on more recent work, including Locke and Latham (2019), Itzchakov and Latham (2018), Chen, Latham, and Piccolo (2020), Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018), and Devine and Ash (2022); and we have added applied work that the reviewerΓÇÖs prior comment first prompted us to incorporate (Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021).
[codex] 62:More importantly, we have also expanded the theoretical framing (pp. X-X) to discuss how the classical feedback literature establishes that pairing feedback with an explicit goal works, but consistent with the broader logic of this literature, feedback regulates behavior only when there is a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. Our argument is that descriptive feedback can also be effective in domains where a strong implicit standard is already entrenched, such that no explicit goal need be paired alongside the feedback to make it useful. More specifically, we discuss how feedback evoking the past treatment of women and racial minorities provides a clean test of this theory. We propose that anti-discrimination law, social and reputational pressures to behave in ways that are not prejudicial, and selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian self-image can jointly sustain an entrenched injunctive norm against prejudiced selection (Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; ├ülvarez-Benjumea, 2023). When descriptive feedback reveals a discrepancy between this implicit standard and past behavior, we theorize that a motivation to respond without prejudice is activated even in the absence of a specific external goal. 
[codex] 63:-I like figure 2.
[codex] 64:-I also like that you mention that these effects might be even stronger with more reputation management public pressure, despite showing that in these studies that part is not necessary.
[codex] 65:RESPONSE: We appreciate your comments on Figure 2 and on our discussion of reputation management, and we are grateful for your thoughtful feedback throughout the review process. 
[codex] 66:Reviewer: 2
[codex] 67:Comments:
[codex] 68:Thanks for the opportunity to review this paper, which has improved substantially since the last round. I appreciate the authorsΓÇÖ attentiveness to most of the comments raised previously. After reading this version, I have two comments.
[codex] 69:RESPONSE: Thank you for noting the improvements to the manuscript. We are grateful for your feedback, which has strengthened the paper.
[codex] 70:First, the paper, as written, feels a bit dated in several spots (e.g., early intro, then pp.4-5, and Discussion) given all that has transpired with respect to pull back on DEI commitments and practices in the US. ItΓÇÖs not clear how many companies are still providing diversity scorecards or numerical feedback about demographic representation, but itΓÇÖs certainly a smaller number than when this research project began, and perhaps, more importantly, the broader tides have shifted. The one sentence on p.5 ΓÇô ΓÇ£and despiteΓÇªΓÇ¥ - is not sufficient and is perhaps misleading. The authors should find a way to acknowledge this through the narrative, and more accurately depict the current state so that the article does not feel timestamped and detached as if it was written in a pre-2024 period. While doing this, they should find a way to reinforce the reasons why their question and intervention remain important.
[codex] 71:RESPONSE: Thank you for this valuable comment and for urging us to highlight the broader contributions of our research that go beyond any particular current state of affairs. We have updated the Introduction (pp. X) and the Discussion to try to avoid the issue that our paper could read as ΓÇ£timestampedΓÇ¥: either in the current era in which there has been backlash against DEI (which may or may not endure), or in the 2020-2024 era of massively increased support for DEI in the United States.
[codex] 72:The revised manuscript now more thoroughly discusses the fluctuating corporate posture toward DEI in the United States, while noting that despite changing tides domestically, regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation is expanding overall internationally. For example, AustraliaΓÇÖs Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023 mandates public reporting of firm-level gender representation and pay-gap data (Ressia, 2024); the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires member-state transposition by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024); and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% representation objective for the underrepresented gender on listed-company boards. 
[codex] 73:
[codex] 74:We also describe how within the U.S., public and stakeholder sentiment has shifted more slowly than corporate and legal rhetoric. For instance a 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reports that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025), and anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at numerous prominent organizations, including Costco, Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others (CBS, 2025; Marketplace, 2025). In addition, many U.S. firms appear to have simply rebranded or reframed diversity-related work rather than dismantling it entirely since 2024. For example, Constellation Brands now uses ΓÇ£Inclusive Culture Team,ΓÇ¥ KohlΓÇÖs has shifted to ΓÇ£Chief Inclusion and Belonging Officer,ΓÇ¥ and Nationwide and UPS have migrated toward ΓÇ£belonging,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£respect,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£fairness,ΓÇ¥ or ΓÇ£inclusive experiencesΓÇ¥ framings (CNBC, 2025; HRGrapevine, 2025; Marketplace, 2026). Consistent with this pattern, Gravity Research reports a 22% decline in Fortune 100 references to ΓÇ£DEI/diversityΓÇ¥ between 2023 and 2024, alongside a 59% year-over-year increase in references to neutral terms like ΓÇ£belongingΓÇ¥ (Gravity Research, 2024).Your feedback helped us sharpen our discussion of why this paperΓÇÖs central theoretical question remains ΓÇ£timeless.ΓÇ¥ Our contribution is not simply to demonstrate that descriptive feedback may serve as a useful managerial tool for organizations seeking to enhance their diversity. Instead, it is to show that descriptive feedback about past selection decisions can change subsequent decisions when the patterns highlighted raise concerns about appearing prejudiced or failing to live up to your own egalitarian standards. To the extent that corporate messaging and formal diversity commitments are one source of peopleΓÇÖs motivation to respond without prejudice, their retreat may weaken the effects we document. However, such organizational commitments are only one potential reason why people prefer not to behave in ways that could be seen as prejudiced. Anti-discrimination law, international transparency requirements, employee and stakeholder expectations, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments continue to make race and gender consequential dimensions of evaluation, even when organizations no longer foreground DEI policies. We now explain that descriptive feedback should be most influential when past selection patterns raise active concerns about prejudice, and less influential in contexts where those concerns are absent, muted, or explicitly rejected. Practically, this also reinforces the relevance of studying descriptive feedback even in the current setting: in settings where organizations are reluctant to issue explicit diversity goals (as they might be in the U.S. at the moment), it arguably becomes more important to understand the effects of other steps companies might take, such as whether making past selection patterns visible can still shape who is subsequently selected, hired, promoted, platformed, or featured.
[codex] 75:
[codex] 76:Somewhat related, I still think more can be done to make the case for the theoretical contribution. Here is one way I think the authors can do this. I think they can start with language that more tentatively bounds the scope and generalizability of the authorsΓÇÖ claims. It currently reads as if this intervention would work similarly in any organizational context. But if the entire process hinges on the motivation to not appear prejudiced, it stands to reason that this motivation will not be the same across culturally heterogeneous organizations, some of which tightly identify with egalitarian ideals and inclusion, whereas others do not, and have recently retreated and even disavowed these ΓÇ£wokeΓÇ¥ metrics in place of a sole focus on merit. The fact that individualsΓÇÖ political ideology (perhaps an indirect proxy for motivation to respond without prejudice) did not work out in Study 4, leaves this somewhat unaddressed empirically. There is a tension here because the author also underscore this motivation to respond without prejudice as central to their theoretical contribution (one of two main contributions). To really nail this mechanism more definitively and show scope conditions (both of which can help solidify the contribution), I could imagine a study in which the authors more directly manipulated aspects of the situation to increase or decrease individualsΓÇÖ motivation to respond without prejudice and then measured the effects on subsequent decision making. This would help them more compellingly account for when these effects do vs do not emerge and why. There are already a bunch of studies in this package, however, so whether the authors should engage this issue empirically or narratively is a question for the editorial team.
[codex] 77:RESPONSE: Thank you for this thoughtful comment. As you note, we did test whether political ideology moderated our effect in Study 4 and overall observed no significant interaction. While we are cautious about over-interpreting null results, the pattern is suggestive that the effect operates across partisan lines, leaving room for the external and internal motivations to respond without prejudice described above to be at work. Consistent with this interpretation, another recent study by Kirgios et al. (2022) found in a field experiment that when seeking help from city counselors, women and racial minorities benefited from explicitly naming their demographic identity in an ask just as much when contacting Republicans and Democrats, and the underlying mechanism identified was a motivation to control prejudice - the same mechanism we identify as mediating our findings. Overall, the existing empirical evidence suggests political ideology does not seem to moderate motivation to control prejudice.
[codex] 78:We share your view that there are already quite a lot of studies in this paper. Rather than adding another, we have sought to engage with the important issues you raise narratively (this also aligns with the DEΓÇÖs guidance to prioritize streamlining the manuscript).  Specifically, we have sought to sharpen our discussion of our theoretical contribution in the revised General Discussion (pp. X), building on the scope-condition discussion already present in the Future Directions and Limitations section.
[codex] 79:In particular, we now explicitly distinguish between two pathways through which descriptive feedback can change selection decisions. One pathway, the external motivation to control prejudice, should be driven both by a firmΓÇÖs norms but also by the fact that selection decisions are often observable to colleagues, job candidates, supervisors, and other stakeholders. The implicit injunctive norm against prejudicial behavior is largely sustained by anti-discrimination laws, employee and customer scrutiny, and broader reputational concerns. The second pathway, internal motivation to control prejudice, by contrast, refers to selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian beliefs and self-image as non-prejudiced decision-makers. This second pathway should not vary with organizational climate, and it is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4 (a study in which feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation to respond without prejudice mediated subsequent selections).
[codex] 80:Motivation to respond without prejudice is a key mechanism isolated in this paper, but it may not be the only mechanism descriptive feedback activates to change behavior. Fairness norms and broader concerns about appropriate representation may also drive the effects of feedback about past selections on future selection decisions (see also Study 5ΓÇÖs mechanism analysis, which found that fairness concerns drive people to select men when women are overrepresented in order to reduce gender imbalance). We now note that it would be valuable for future research to explore these additional plausible contributing mechanisms. 
