[codex] 105:
[codex] 106:>  In recent years, the rhetoric organizations use around DEI has ebbed and flowed, expanding in some periods and contracting in others. We argue, however, that the interventionΓÇÖs effect is not contingent on these shifts, because both pathways that drive it sit largely outside any one organizationΓÇÖs stated commitments. The external pathway is broader than firm-level climate: a decision makerΓÇÖs selections are observed by coworkers, direct reports, candidates, and other professional peers, and these observers continue to form opinions about whether the selections are fair regardless of how a firm publicly describes its DEI commitments. Anti-discrimination law and everyday workplace norms also continue to apply (Levi & Fried, 2024). The internal pathway is even less sensitive to organizational rhetoric. It reflects a decision makerΓÇÖs own commitment to fairness and desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced (Plant & Devine, 1998), and Study 4 most directly supports this pathway, where feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation emerged as the primary driver of subsequent selections.
