[codex] 12:Descriptive Feedback about Diversity-Related Decisions
[codex] 18:Summary of the Current Research
[codex] 28:Overview of Studies
[codex] 35:Study 1
[codex] 38:Methods
[codex] 39:Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/vazsm/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (55.4% women; 43.7% men; 0.9% non-binary; Mage = 43.80; 72.3% White, 13.2% Black, 6.5% Hispanic, 7.2% Asian).
[codex] 40:Procedure. Participants were told to imagine they worked as producers at NPR and were responsible for identifying and booking expert sources to interview for various news segments and stories. Participants were informed that for the past three months, they had been working on a series of stories about the future of work in America and had selected and interviewed a portfolio of ten experts for these stories.
[codex] 41:Participants were then randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback summarizing the percentage of experts they had selected over the past three months who (1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a university. Notably, NPR has actually tracked each of these attributes of expert sources, which were deemed a priority, and displayed them to producers. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women, presented alongside two of the three statistics presented in the no gender feedback condition drawn at random. 
[codex] 47:Results
[codex] 50:Discussion
[codex] 51:Study 1 mirrored a real organizational practice currently deployed by NPR and provides initial evidence that descriptive feedback about the gender composition of past selections can increase the subsequent selection of women, more so than feedback about other attributes. In our next study, we examine whether our effects hold when people make real, consequential decisions in the field rather than hypothetical choices in an online survey.
[codex] 56:Study 2
[codex] 59:Methods
[codex] 60:Participants. This study was pre-registered on AsPredicted (https://aspredicted.org/WYY_3PL). We recruited 302 participants to complete a 1-minute survey in exchange for a candy bar (52.52% men; 44.96% women; Mage = 25.11, 41.37% White, 10.79% Black, 4.68% Hispanic, 42.81% Asian) in a high-traffic pedestrian area at a midsize university in the Northeastern United States between March 27 and May 15, 2024. The IRB approved a waiver of informed consent, so participants were not told that they were participating in a research study.
[codex] 61:Procedure. Student recruiters in school-branded clothing (truthfully) told passersby they were conducting a quick vote on which biographies should be displayed at the business school to encourage non-fiction reading; seven books with obscured covers on a table served as a visual prop (see Figure S1 in the Appendix). Participants who agreed were handed an iPad showing 25 well-known biographies, each with a cover thumbnail and a brief description (protagonistΓÇÖs name, role, publication year, page count); five (20%) featured women protagonists.
[codex] 62:Participants were instructed to vote for an initial portfolio of six biographies they would recommend for the on-campus display. After making their initial selections, participants were randomly assigned to either (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants were presented with three pieces of descriptive feedback about their initial six book selections, specifically the percentage of biographies they had selected that (1) were over 500 pages, (2) were written in the past 25 years, and (3) featured an entertainer. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of biographies they had selected featuring a woman protagonist alongside two additional pieces of descriptive feedback that were randomly drawn from the list of three descriptive facts provided in the no gender feedback condition. After receiving descriptive feedback about the composition of their initial selected portfolio of six biographies, participants were asked to vote for a seventh and final biography from the original setΓÇôwhere their prior selections were highlightedΓÇôto include in the display.
[codex] 66:Results 
[codex] 69:Discussion
[codex] 71:Study 3
[codex] 74:Study 3A
[codex] 78:Methods
[codex] 79:Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/4z8hk), we recruited 1,000 participants on AmazonΓÇÖs Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (46.1% men; 51.4% women; Mage = 42.20; 72.3% White, 12.0% Black, 6.2% Hispanic, 8.8% Asian).
[codex] 80:Procedure. Participants were truthfully informed about a real Facebook campaign to advertise popular and inspirational biographical films (ΓÇ£biopicsΓÇ¥) and asked to weigh in on which films to include. Participants saw25 candidate films each with a cover art thumbnail and a brief description listing the  protagonistΓÇÖs name (e.g., Judy Garland, Alan Turing), claim to fame (e.g., Actress, WWII codebreaker), the filmΓÇÖs year of release (e.g., 2019, 2014), and budget (e.g., $10m, $14m); 4 of the25 films (16%) featured a racial minority protagonist. 
[codex] 81:Participants selected a portfolio of seven films for the Facebook campaign and  were incentivized for the quality of their decisions. Specifically, we (truthfully) told participants: ΓÇ£To provide extra motivation to take this seriously, weΓÇÖll send you a $5 bonus if your list is selected (there will be an eventual vote on all of the lists generated).ΓÇ¥ 
[codex] 82:Participants were then randomly assigned to either (1) the no race feedback or (2) the race feedback condition. In the no race feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback on the percentage of films that (1) had a budget above $40M, (2) were released after 2010, and (3) were over 2 hours long. In the race feedback condition, participants always received descriptive feedback about the percentage of films they had selected that featured a racial minority protagonist alongside two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list of film attributes summarized in the no race feedback condition. After receiving descriptive feedback on their initial film selections, participants selected an eighth and final film for the Facebook campaign from the original set, where their prior selections were highlighted. See Materials Section: Study 3A in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] 83:Results
[codex] 84:ParticipantsΓÇÖ initial selections featured racial minority protagonists 16.1% of the time, with balance across conditions (p┬á= .314, see Appendix Table S3). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors to predict whether the eighth and final biopic selected featured a racial minority protagonist, using assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist in the race feedback condition (27.10% chose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist) than in the no race feedback condition (17.73% chose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist;┬áB┬á= 0.094, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.145],┬át(998) = 3.57,┬áp┬á< .001).The effect of assignment to the race feedback condition on the subsequent selection of a racial minority protagonist was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about any of the three comparison attributes (all pΓÇÖs Γëñ .009; see Table S3, Models 5-8 for the per-study system-of-equations results). 
[codex] 85:Study 3B
[codex] 87:Methods
[codex] 88:Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/uyn8g/), we recruited 1,000 participants on Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (51.0% men; 48.3% women; Mage = 43.60; 77.9% White, 9.7% Black, 5.5% Hispanic, 6.4% Asian).
[codex] 89:Procedure. The procedure in this study was nearly identical to the procedure described in Study 3A, but we changed the selection set of biopics to include 19 films featuring male protagonists and 6 featuring female protagonists (so 24% of the protagonists were women). Participants also began by selecting an initial portfolio of six films for inclusion in the Facebook advertising campaign instead of seven. The brief description provided of each film did not state the length of the film; instead, it presented information about the film protagonistΓÇÖs profession (e.g., ΓÇ£A film about George W. Bush. Who was he? 43rd U.S. President.ΓÇ¥). 
[codex] 91:Results
[codex] 93:Discussion
[codex] 96:Study 4
[codex] 101:Study 4A
[codex] 103:Methods
[codex] 104:Participants. As pre-registered (https://aspredicted.org/XGG_21R), we recruited 1,000 participants on AmazonΓÇÖs Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (47.6% men, 51.5% women; Mage = 42.53; 75.75% White, 9.21% Black, 4.75% Hispanic, 8.83% Asian). 
[codex] 105:Procedure. Participants imagined being  tasked with creating a reading list for their local library. They were presented with a 25 (real) authors, each shown with a small photograph and a brief description listing the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., James Baldwin, Isabel Allende), most notable work (e.g., Go Tell It on the Mountain, The House of the Spirits), and a count of their total published works (e.g., ΓÇ£authored 6 books and several short stories and poemsΓÇ¥; ΓÇ£authored 6 booksΓÇ¥). Eight of the 25 authors (32%) were racial minorities.
[codex] 106:Participants selected an initial portfolio of six authors and were randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no race feedback condition or (2) the race feedback condition. In the no race feedback condition, participants received summary statistics about the percentage of selected authors who (1) were born in the 1800s, (2) wrote more than 10 books, and/or (3) wrote poetry. In the race feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of authors they had selected who were racial minorities, alongside one or two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list above.
[codex] 110:Results
[codex] 112:Mediation. Following our pre-registration, we tested each proposed mediator independently using a 10,000-sample bootstrapped mediation model and a Sobel test. The 95% bias-corrected CI for the size of the indirect effect of internal motivation to respond without prejudice excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.06, 95% CI = [0.034, 0.09], suggesting that internal motivation to respond without prejudice helped account for the effect of assignment to the race feedback condition on selecting a racial minority as the final author. Using Imai et al.ΓÇÖs (2010) average causal mediation effect approach, 44.7% of the effect occurred through mediation by the participantΓÇÖs internal motivation to respond without prejudice. In addition, the 95% bias-corrected CI for the size of the indirect effect of external motivation to respond without prejudice excludes zero (indirect effect = 0.019, 95% CI = [0.005, 0.03]), suggesting that participantsΓÇÖ external motivation to respond without prejudice also helped account for the effect of assignment to the race feedback condition (vs. no race feedback) on selecting a racial minority final author. The average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 14.1% of the effect occurred through external motivation to respond without prejudice. 
[codex] 114:Study 4B
[codex] 117:Methods
[codex] 119:Procedure. As in Study 4A, a list of 25 (real) authors was presented to each participant to consider for inclusion in a reading list for their local library. Each author was displayed with a photograph, the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., Kurt Vonnegut), most notable work (e.g., Slaughterhouse-Five), an estimate of their most notable workΓÇÖs all-time sales and time in print (e.g., 800K copies sold, in print 56 years), their number of works authored (e.g., 14 books, 3 essays), and their genre(s) (e.g., Science Fiction, Satire). Six of the authors on this list (24%) were women.
[codex] 124:Results 
[codex] 128:Mediation. Following our pre-registration, we tested each proposed mediator independently using a 10,000-sample bootstrapped mediation model and a Sobel test (Imai et al., 2010). The 95% bias-corrected CI for the indirect effect of internal motivation to respond without prejudice excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.064, 95% CI = [0.037, 0.094]), suggesting that internal motivation partially accounted for the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a woman as the final author; the average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 53.9% of the effect occurred through internal motivation. Next, the 95% bias-corrected CI for the indirect effect of external motivation excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.030, 95% CI = [0.014, 0.048]), suggesting that external motivation likewise accounted for the effect; the average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 24.8% of the effect occurred through external motivation. 
[codex] 131:Discussion
[codex] 134:Study 5
[codex] 145:Methods
[codex] 147:Participants. As pre-registered (https://aspredicted.org/xt2ct6), we recruited 1,200 participants through Prolific Academic to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (39.3% men, 59.0% women, 1.6% non-binary/other; Mage = 42.7; 70.0% White, 11.2% Black, 9.3% Hispanic, 8.4% Asian).
[codex] 148:Procedure. Following a similar procedure to Studies 2ΓÇô4 participants imagined  planning a major international business conference and selecting a panel of six business leaders (from a list of 25 real leaders in randomized order) to provide insights into the global business landscape.We included each leaderΓÇÖs name (e.g., Jeff Bezos, Mary Barra), title (e.g., Founder, CEO), and company affiliation (e.g., Amazon, General Motors). After making their initial six-person panel, participants were randomly assigned to one of four conditions in a 2 (gender feedback vs. no gender feedback) X 2 (women underrepresented vs. women overrepresented) design. Participants randomly assigned to the women underrepresented conditions made selections from a panelist candidate list including 18 men and 6 women (25% women). In the women overrepresented conditions, participants made selections from a panelist candidate list including 18 women and 6 men (75% women). Participants in the no gender feedback conditions were randomly assigned to receive separate summary statistics about both the percentage of panelists they initially selected who were (1) in the tech industry and (2) company founders. In the gender feedback conditions, participants received feedback about the percentage of panelists they had selected who were women as well as the two summary statistics about past selectees that were provided to participants in the no gender feedback condition. We ensured balance in the fraction of men and women candidates who were in the tech industry and company founders across the women underrepresented and women overrepresented conditions. After receiving feedback, participants selected a seventh and final panelist from the original set, and their prior selections were highlighted.
[codex] 151:Results
[codex] 152:Participants in all conditions first selected six panelists. In the women overrepresented condition, 60.7% of these initial selectees were women (balance was successfully achieved on this attribute: 59.8% of initial selectees were women in the no gender feedback condition and 61.6% were women in the gender feedback condition, t(599.9) = -1.11, p = .268, 95% CI = [-0.049, 0.014]). In the women underrepresented condition, 21.0% of initial selectees were women (balance was successfully achieved on this attribute: 20.5% of initial selectees were women in the no gender feedback condition and 21.4% were women in the gender feedback condition, t(596) = -0.49, p = .624, 95% CI = [-0.045, 0.027]).
