[codex] 38-Methods
[codex] 39-Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/vazsm/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (55.4% women; 43.7% men; 0.9% non-binary; Mage = 43.80; 72.3% White, 13.2% Black, 6.5% Hispanic, 7.2% Asian).
[codex] 40-Procedure. Participants were told to imagine they worked as producers at NPR and were responsible for identifying and booking expert sources to interview for various news segments and stories. Participants were informed that for the past three months, they had been working on a series of stories about the future of work in America and had selected and interviewed a portfolio of ten experts for these stories.
[codex] 41:Participants were then randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback summarizing the percentage of experts they had selected over the past three months who (1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a university. Notably, NPR has actually tracked each of these attributes of expert sources, which were deemed a priority, and displayed them to producers. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women, presented alongside two of the three statistics presented in the no gender feedback condition drawn at random. 
[codex] 42-After receiving descriptive feedback about the composition of their past expert selections, participants were asked to select three experts from a list of 25 candidates for an upcoming NPR segment on how artificial intelligence is reshaping employment and were provided with each candidate's name, area of expertise, and institutional affiliation. See Materials Section: Study 1 in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] 43:Prior to data collection, we ran a pre-registered pretest (https://aspredicted.org/xa7u94.pdf; N = 300 Prolific participants) to compare the rated importance of the four attributes featured in Study 1 for selecting NPR experts. Each participant was randomly assigned to rate one attribute on a scale from 1 (ΓÇ£Not at all importantΓÇ¥) to 7 (ΓÇ£Very importantΓÇ¥). Compared to gender (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥: M = 3.87, SD = 1.92, n = 75), participants rated ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ as significantly more important (M = 4.50, SD = 1.48, n = 74; t(139.0) = 2.26, p = .026, d = 0.37) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ as similarly important (M = 4.05, SD = 1.74, n = 75; t(146.6) = 0.62, p = .534, d = 0.10). ΓÇ£Were based on the West Coast of the United StatesΓÇ¥ was rated as less important than gender (M = 3.11, SD = 1.81, n = 74; t(146.7) = 2.48, p = .014, d = 0.41; full results in Appendix Section S[X]). Two of the three comparison attributes were thus rated as at least as important as gender. These results suggest that differences in the perceived importance of the type of feedback participants receive about their selections in Study 1 are unlikely to account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections.
