[codex] 164-Results
[codex] 165-The results of this simulation exercise are summarized in Appendix Table S12 (and the complete regressions used to estimate the effect of each simulated quota condition are presented in detail in Appendix Table S14). For women in Study 2 (see Appendix Table S12, Row 1), compared to the control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention increased the likelihood that participants selected biographies featuring female protagonists by 13.2 percentage points (B = 0.132, 95% CI = [0.031, 0.234], p = .011), and the simulated quota also significantly increased selections, by 18.5% (B = 0.185, 95% CI = [0.082, 0.289], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 71.4% of the benefit of a quota. For racial minorities in Study 3A (see Appendix Table S12, Row 2), compared to the control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention increased the likelihood that participants selected films featuring racial minority protagonists by 9.4 percentage points (B = 0.094, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.145], p < .001), and the simulated quota also significantly increased selections, by 17.1% (B = 0.171, 95% CI = [0.118, 0.225], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 54.7% of the benefit of a quota. For women in Study 3B (see Appendix Table S12, Row 3), compared to control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting films featuring female protagonists by 20.6 percentage points (B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 25.7% (B = 0.257, 95% CI = [0.201, 0.313], p < .001). This means offering descriptive feedback on the gender of past filmsΓÇÖ protagonists yielded 80.0% of the benefit of a gender quota. In Study 4A (see Appendix Table S12, Row 4), which examined racial diversity in author selections, compared to the control condition the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting authors from racial minority backgrounds by 13.4 percentage points (B = 0.134, 95% CI = [0.075, 0.193], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 29.6% (B = 0.296, 95% CI = [0.237, 0.355], p < .001), relative to the control condition, meaning that feedback achieved 45.3% of the effect of a quota. Finally, in Study 4B (see Appendix Table S12, Row 5), which examined gender diversity in author selections, compared to the control condition the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting female authors by 11.9 percentage points (B = 0.119, 95% CI = [0.060, 0.178], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 15.6% (B = 0.156, 95% CI = [0.096, 0.215], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 76.7% of the benefit of a quota.
[codex] 166-In summary, these simulations reveal that across our studies, our light-touch descriptive feedback intervention produced 45% to 80% (and 71% of the benefits in our field study) of the increase in selecteesΓÇÖ diversity that would be achieved by taking a heavy-handed (and often illegal) quota-based approach to promoting diversity. These findings underscore the practical value of descriptive feedback as an intervention that can achieve substantial diversity gains while remaining both legally permissible and minimally invasive.
[codex] 167:General Discussion
[codex] 168-        	Across seven pre-registered experiments, including a framed field study in a real organization, we investigate the impact of providing descriptive feedback about the gender and racial diversity of past candidate selections on evaluatorsΓÇÖ future choices. In Studies 1-5 we demonstrate that when women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented in candidate pools, giving participants feedback about the fraction of women (or racial minorities) they initially select increases the likelihood that they will subsequently choose to add a woman (or racial minority) to their portfolio. By contrast, when participants receive descriptive feedback about the fraction of selectees with other domain-relevant attributes that are DEI-irrelevant (e.g., the fraction of Technologists on a panel instead of the fraction of women on that panel), it does not have the same impact on their subsequent selections (i.e., they are less likely to subsequently select a Technologist). In Studies 4A and 4B, we identify peopleΓÇÖs motivation to respond without prejudice as a key mechanism underlying the effect of descriptive feedback on peopleΓÇÖs subsequent DEI-related selection decisions. We find that both internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice mediates the relationship between receiving descriptive feedback about past selectees and making more gender-or-racially-diverse future candidate selections. 
[codex] 169-However, we do find an important moderator of our effect: in settings where feedback highlights that candidates who have historically faced discrimination are overrepresented among selectees, the effect shrinks and reverses, prompting people to strive for parity by adjusting their picks in the opposite direction (see Study 5).
