[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:74:We also describe how within the U.S., public and stakeholder sentiment has shifted more slowly than corporate and legal rhetoric. For instance a 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reports that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025), and anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at numerous prominent organizations, including Costco, Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others (CBS, 2025; Marketplace, 2025). In addition, many U.S. firms appear to have simply rebranded or reframed diversity-related work rather than dismantling it entirely since 2024. For example, Constellation Brands now uses ΓÇ£Inclusive Culture Team,ΓÇ¥ KohlΓÇÖs has shifted to ΓÇ£Chief Inclusion and Belonging Officer,ΓÇ¥ and Nationwide and UPS have migrated toward ΓÇ£belonging,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£respect,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£fairness,ΓÇ¥ or ΓÇ£inclusive experiencesΓÇ¥ framings (CNBC, 2025; HRGrapevine, 2025; Marketplace, 2026). Consistent with this pattern, Gravity Research reports a 22% decline in Fortune 100 references to ΓÇ£DEI/diversityΓÇ¥ between 2023 and 2024, alongside a 59% year-over-year increase in references to neutral terms like ΓÇ£belongingΓÇ¥ (Gravity Research, 2024).Your feedback helped us sharpen our discussion of why this paperΓÇÖs central theoretical question remains ΓÇ£timeless.ΓÇ¥ Our contribution is not simply to demonstrate that descriptive feedback may serve as a useful managerial tool for organizations seeking to enhance their diversity. Instead, it is to show that descriptive feedback about past selection decisions can change subsequent decisions when the patterns highlighted raise concerns about appearing prejudiced or failing to live up to your own egalitarian standards. To the extent that corporate messaging and formal diversity commitments are one source of peopleΓÇÖs motivation to respond without prejudice, their retreat may weaken the effects we document. However, such organizational commitments are only one potential reason why people prefer not to behave in ways that could be seen as prejudiced. Anti-discrimination law, international transparency requirements, employee and stakeholder expectations, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments continue to make race and gender consequential dimensions of evaluation, even when organizations no longer foreground DEI policies. We now explain that descriptive feedback should be most influential when past selection patterns raise active concerns about prejudice, and less influential in contexts where those concerns are absent, muted, or explicitly rejected. Practically, this also reinforces the relevance of studying descriptive feedback even in the current setting: in settings where organizations are reluctant to issue explicit diversity goals (as they might be in the U.S. at the moment), it arguably becomes more important to understand the effects of other steps companies might take, such as whether making past selection patterns visible can still shape who is subsequently selected, hired, promoted, platformed, or featured.
