[codex] manuscript_pending_suggestions.md:106:>  In recent years, the rhetoric organizations use around DEI has ebbed and flowed, expanding in some periods and contracting in others. We argue, however, that the interventionΓÇÖs effect is not contingent on these shifts, because both pathways that drive it sit largely outside any one organizationΓÇÖs stated commitments. The external pathway is broader than firm-level climate: a decision makerΓÇÖs selections are observed by coworkers, direct reports, candidates, and other professional peers, and these observers continue to form opinions about whether the selections are fair regardless of how a firm publicly describes its DEI commitments. Anti-discrimination law and everyday workplace norms also continue to apply (Levi & Fried, 2024). The internal pathway is even less sensitive to organizational rhetoric. It reflects a decision makerΓÇÖs own commitment to fairness and desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced (Plant & Devine, 1998), and Study 4 most directly supports this pathway, where feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation emerged as the primary driver of subsequent selections.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:34:RESPONSE: The Introduction and General Discussion now draw on more contemporary work in the feedback, goalΓÇæsetting, and socialΓÇænorms literatures (e.g., Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018; Devine & Ash, 2022; Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021), alongside the foundational citations from our original manuscript, which we have retained. We have also expanded our IntroductionΓÇÖs theorizing (pp. XΓÇæX) to clarify why descriptive feedback should shift selection decisions about women and underrepresented minorities even without a paired explicit goal: we argue that there is a strong, implicit injunctive norm in this setting against prejudiced selection, and feedback makes prior behavior that could be interpreted as prejudiced salient alongside that implicit norm, which provokes behavior change. We address Reviewer 1ΓÇÖs specific suggestions in detail on Pages X-X of this response letter.
