otential reason why people prefer not to behave in ways that could be seen as prejudiced. Anti-discrimination law, international transparency requirements, employee and stakeholder expectations, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments continue to make race and gender consequential dimensions of evaluation, even when organizations no longer foreground DEI policies. We now explain that descriptive feedback should be most influential when past selection patterns raise active concerns about prejudice, and less influential in contexts where those concerns are absent, muted, or explicitly rejected. Practically, this also reinforces the relevance of studying descriptive feedback even in the current setting: in settings where organizations are reluctant to issue explicit diversity goals (as they might be in the U.S. at the moment), it arguably becomes more important to understand the effects of other steps companies might take, such as whether making past selection patterns visible can still shape who is subsequently selected, hired, promoted, platformed, or featured.
