[codex] 88-Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/uyn8g/), we recruited 1,000 participants on Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (51.0% men; 48.3% women; Mage = 43.60; 77.9% White, 9.7% Black, 5.5% Hispanic, 6.4% Asian).
[codex] 89-Procedure. The procedure in this study was nearly identical to the procedure described in Study 3A, but we changed the selection set of biopics to include 19 films featuring male protagonists and 6 featuring female protagonists (so 24% of the protagonists were women). Participants also began by selecting an initial portfolio of six films for inclusion in the Facebook advertising campaign instead of seven. The brief description provided of each film did not state the length of the film; instead, it presented information about the film protagonistΓÇÖs profession (e.g., ΓÇ£A film about George W. Bush. Who was he? 43rd U.S. President.ΓÇ¥). 
[codex] 90:Just as in the prior study, after making their set of six initial film selections, participants were randomly assigned to either (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants were presented with feedback about the percentage of films they had selected that (1) had a budget above $40M, (2) were released after 2010, and (3) included a political leader as the protagonist. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of films they had selected featuring a woman protagonist, in addition to two more pieces of descriptive feedback randomly selected from the three in the no gender feedback condition. Otherwise, the study was identical to Study 3A. See Materials Section: Study 3B in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] 91-Results
[codex] 92:On average, 17.5% of participantsΓÇÖ initially selected films featured female protagonists, with balance across conditions (p = 0.813; see Appendix Table/Section X). As shown in Figure S2B and in our primary, pre-registered OLS regression (Model 1 of Table S5), participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a woman protagonist as their seventh and final film in the gender feedback condition (40.64% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist) than in the no gender feedback condition (20.08% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist; B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], t(998) = 7.24, p < .001, see Table S5 Model 1). These results were robust to several alternative specifications, including controlling for participant gender, race, and age, and analyzing our data with logistic regression (see Appendix Table S6 for robustness checks). In addition, as shown in Figure S2B and Table S5 (Models 5-8), and as predicted, the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a 7th film with a woman protagonist was larger than the effect of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of initial films selected with a (1) budget above $40M (F(1, 1992) = 65.06, p < .001), (2) political leader protagonist (F(1, 1992) = 57.74, p < .001), or (3) release year after 2010 (F(1, 1992) = 12.44, p < .001) on subsequent selections of a 7th and final biopic with, respectively, a (1) budget above $40M, (2) political leader protagonist, or (3) release year after 2010 (in fact, all other types of feedback had insignificant effects on subsequent film selections).
[codex] 93-Discussion
[codex] 94-Across two incentivized experiments,  descriptive feedback about the race (Study 3A) or gender (Study 3B) of protagonists featured in previously selected films increased subsequent selections of films featuring racial minorities or women, respectively. One possible explanation for our findings is that the feedback itself signaled that we value racial or gender diversity: after initially choosing films based on personal preferences, participants may have inferred from race or gender feedback that these attributes mattered to the experimenter and attended to these attributes more in subsequent decisions as a result of a ΓÇ£demand effectΓÇ¥ (Orne, 1962; Zizzo, 2010). If this alternative explanation were driving our effects, however, we would also expect participants to respond to the ΓÇ£demand effectΓÇ¥ inherent in receiving feedback about other attributes of their selected films (e.g., feedback about a filmΓÇÖs budget or year of release), but we found no such patterns. 
