[codex] 66-Results 
[codex] 67-Initial selections featured women protagonists 25.2% of the time, with a slight imbalance across conditions (23.0% control vs. 27.3% treatment, p = .050). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors to predict whether the seventh and final biography participants selected featured a woman. Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biography featuring a woman as their seventh and final selection in the gender feedback condition (35.10% did so) than in the no gender feedback condition (21.85% chose a woman; B = 0.132, 95% CI = [0.031, 0.234],┬át(302) = 2.56,┬áp┬á= .011, see Figure 3; Table 3, Model 1).
[codex] 68:As was the case in Study 1, we found no significant effects of the impact of random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about another given biography attribute in a participantΓÇÖs initial portfolio of choices on subsequent selections of biographies with that same attribute (all pΓÇÖs ΓëÑ .5; see Table 3 Models 2-4). 
[codex] 69-Discussion
[codex] 70-	Study 2 extends our findings in two important ways. First, we find that the effect persists in a field setting where participants made consequential choices. Second, unlike Study 1, here  participants received feedback about their own prior selections rather than hypothetical decisionsΓÇöconfirming that the effect arises even when people reflect on their own past choices. In the next study, we test whether providing feedback about the racial composition of past selectees increases future selections of racial minorities in an incentivized experiment. 
