[codex] 103-Methods
[codex] --
[codex] 105-Procedure. Participants imagined being  tasked with creating a reading list for their local library. They were presented with a 25 (real) authors, each shown with a small photograph and a brief description listing the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., James Baldwin, Isabel Allende), most notable work (e.g., Go Tell It on the Mountain, The House of the Spirits), and a count of their total published works (e.g., ΓÇ£authored 6 books and several short stories and poemsΓÇ¥; ΓÇ£authored 6 booksΓÇ¥). Eight of the 25 authors (32%) were racial minorities.
[codex] 106-Participants selected an initial portfolio of six authors and were randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no race feedback condition or (2) the race feedback condition. In the no race feedback condition, participants received summary statistics about the percentage of selected authors who (1) were born in the 1800s, (2) wrote more than 10 books, and/or (3) wrote poetry. In the race feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of authors they had selected who were racial minorities, alongside one or two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list above.
[codex] 107:After receiving feedback, participants selected a seventh and final author to recommend for their local libraryΓÇÖs summer fiction reading list from the original author candidate set, where their prior selections were highlighted. Finally, participants were asked questions to assess their internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. See Materials Section: Study 4A for full study materials. 
[codex] 108-Internal motivation to respond without prejudice. To assess internal motives (e.g., image concerns) in the final author selection, we adapted four items from Plant and DevineΓÇÖs (1998) internal motivation to respond without prejudice scale (e.g., ΓÇ£Given my personal values and beliefs, an important factor in my selection of the seventh author to add to my list was my desire to promote the success of racial minorities.ΓÇ¥; CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.93). Items used a  1 (Strongly disagree) to 7 (Strongly agree) scale and, as pre-registered, were separately z-scored and then averaged.
[codex] 109-External motivation to respond without prejudice. To assess external motives (e.g., reputational concerns) in the final author selection,  we adapted three items from Plant and DevineΓÇÖs external motivation to respond without prejudice scale (e.g., ΓÇ£When making my decision about who to select as my seventh author, I considered the social pressures I face to appear to promote racial minorities where they are typically underrepresented.ΓÇ¥; CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.90). Items used a 1 (Strongly disagree) to 7 (Strongly agree) scale, and as pre-registered, were separately z-scored and then averaged. 
[codex] 110-Results
[codex] 111:Initial selections featured racial minority authors 21.8% of the time, with balance across conditions (p┬á= .114; see Appendix Table S7). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors predicting whether the seventh and final author a participant selected was a racial minority, with assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor. We again replicated the findings from our previous studies (see Table S7 for complete results): Participants were significantly more likely to choose a racial minority author in the race feedback condition (41.60% chose a racial minority author) than in the no race feedback condition (28.20% chose a racial minority author;┬áB┬á= 0.134, 95% CI = [0.075, 0.193],┬át(998) = 4.48,┬áp┬á< .001; see Table S7, Model 1). In addition, as predicted, we again found that the effect of providing feedback about the race of initial selectees is significantly larger than the effects of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of initial selectees (poets:┬áF(1, 3984) = 6.19,┬áp┬á= .013; wrote > 10 books:┬áF(1, 3984) = 5.50,┬áp┬á= .019; born in 1800s:┬áF(1, 3984) = 5.26,┬áp┬á= .022; see Table S7, Models 5-8).
[codex] 112-Mediation. Following our pre-registration, we tested each proposed mediator independently using a 10,000-sample bootstrapped mediation model and a Sobel test. The 95% bias-corrected CI for the size of the indirect effect of internal motivation to respond without prejudice excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.06, 95% CI = [0.034, 0.09], suggesting that internal motivation to respond without prejudice helped account for the effect of assignment to the race feedback condition on selecting a racial minority as the final author. Using Imai et al.ΓÇÖs (2010) average causal mediation effect approach, 44.7% of the effect occurred through mediation by the participantΓÇÖs internal motivation to respond without prejudice. In addition, the 95% bias-corrected CI for the size of the indirect effect of external motivation to respond without prejudice excludes zero (indirect effect = 0.019, 95% CI = [0.005, 0.03]), suggesting that participantsΓÇÖ external motivation to respond without prejudice also helped account for the effect of assignment to the race feedback condition (vs. no race feedback) on selecting a racial minority final author. The average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 14.1% of the effect occurred through external motivation to respond without prejudice. 
[codex] 113-We next tested for both mediators in a multiple mediation model (as preregistered), which addressed address potential multicollinearity between these correlated measures (rΓÇë=ΓÇë0.72, p < 0.001). Once accounting for the correlation between constructs, internal motivation to respond without prejudice (indirect effect = 0.08, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.11]), significantly mediated the effect  whereas external motivation to respond without prejudice (indirect effect = -0.014, 95% CI = [-0.03, 0.00]) did not.  
[codex] 114-Study 4B
[codex] 115:In this study, we replicate our key findings from Study 4A, but this time we provide feedback about the gender (rather than race) of the initial selectees. Prior to this study, we conducted a pretest (N = 550) rating 21 candidate author attributes on importance for selecting authors (see Appendix Section S4 for full details); allowing us to select three comparison attributes that did not differ significantly from gender on rated importance.
[codex] 116-Given that liberals and conservatives differ not only in their attitudes toward diversity but also in their understanding of what diversity means (Howard, Cervone, & Motyl, 2022), and that recent research suggests diversity initiatives may produce divergent reactions across the political spectrum (Hachem & Dover, 2024), we also examine whether participantsΓÇÖ political ideology moderates the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender of past selectees.
[codex] 117-Methods
[codex] 118-	Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/de3bu/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific Academic to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (48.0% men, 50.7% women, 1.1% non-binary; Mage = 43.0; 75.9% White, 10.8% Black, 4.8% Hispanic, 8.0% Asian).
[codex] 119:Procedure. As in Study 4A, a list of 25 (real) authors was presented to each participant to consider for inclusion in a reading list for their local library. Each author was displayed with a photograph, the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., Kurt Vonnegut), most notable work (e.g., Slaughterhouse-Five), an estimate of their most notable workΓÇÖs all-time sales and time in print (e.g., 800K copies sold, in print 56 years), their number of works authored (e.g., 14 books, 3 essays), and their genre(s) (e.g., Science Fiction, Satire). Six of the authors on this list (24%) were women.
[codex] 120:Following a similar procedure to the one described in Study 4A, participants were randomly assigned to one of two conditions: participants in the no gender feedback condition received summary statistics about the percentage of authors they had selected who (1) wrote works spanning multiple genres, (2) had at least one book with 30 million or more copies sold, and/or (3) had works that remained in continuous print for over 50 years. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of authors they had selected who were women, alongside two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list of items in the no gender feedback condition. After receiving feedback, participants selected a seventh and final author to recommend for their local libraryΓÇÖs winter fiction reading list from the original candidate set, where their prior selections were highlighted. 
[codex] 121:After making all decisions, participants were asked questions to assess their internal (CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.93) and external (CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.89) motivation to respond without prejudice, which were identical to the questions in Study 4A except for word changes made to focus on avoiding gender prejudice rather than racial prejudice. See Materials Section: Study 4B for full study materials. 
[codex] 122-Political ideology. To measure participantsΓÇÖ political orientation, we used the 7-point political ideology scale from the American National Election Studies (ANES, 2022). Participants responded to the prompt ΓÇ£When it comes to politics, do you usually think of yourself as...?ΓÇ¥ on a scale ranging from 1 (Extremely liberal) to 7 (Extremely conservative), with 4 representing Moderate; middle of the road. This measure was centered at 4 (moderate) for analyses examining moderation effects.
[codex] 123-Political party affiliation. To assess participantsΓÇÖ political party identification, we adapted the party identification item from the American National Election Studies (ANES, 2022). Participants were asked ΓÇ£Generally speaking, do you usually think of yourself as a Republican, a Democrat, or an Independent?ΓÇ¥ and selected one of three options: Democrat, Republican, or Independent. For regression analyses, party affiliation was dummy coded with Republican as the reference category.
