[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:14:We have streamlined the empirical sections of the paper following your guidance on reducing length and repetition. The revised manuscript is now [X] pages shorter than our last draft, and the Methods and Results sections of each study have been shortened (the later studies have been tightened the most) to avoid unnecessary redundancy.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:16:To address your concern that participants might already use comparison attributes ΓÇ£appropriatelyΓÇ¥ in their initial selections (potentially explaining why feedback about race and gender appears uniquely effective in our studies), we conducted a new pooled analysis of Studies 2, 3, and 4B restricting our analyses to participants whose initial selections contained zero books or films with a given attribute. We propose this is a conservative signal of underrepresentation that should provoke a reaction to feedback regardless of which attribute is involved. Within this sample, we (unsurprisingly) still find that feedback about the race or gender of prior selectees significantly increased the probability of subsequently selecting a racial minority or woman, respectively. However, feedback about all other attributes from our studies pooled (e.g., a filmΓÇÖs year of release, a protagonistΓÇÖs profession) did not significantly change subsequent selections in the predicted direction if an absence of an attribute signals an ΓÇ£inappropriateΓÇ¥ level of representation. A Wald test confirms the difference in the effects of feedback about zero representation on these dimensions (race/gender vs. other attributes) is significant. We describe these new analyses in more detail below and in our revised manuscript on page X.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:34:RESPONSE: The Introduction and General Discussion now draw on more contemporary work in the feedback, goalΓÇæsetting, and socialΓÇænorms literatures (e.g., Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018; Devine & Ash, 2022; Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021), alongside the foundational citations from our original manuscript, which we have retained. We have also expanded our IntroductionΓÇÖs theorizing (pp. XΓÇæX) to clarify why descriptive feedback should shift selection decisions about women and underrepresented minorities even without a paired explicit goal: we argue that there is a strong, implicit injunctive norm in this setting against prejudiced selection, and feedback makes prior behavior that could be interpreted as prejudiced salient alongside that implicit norm, which provokes behavior change. We address Reviewer 1ΓÇÖs specific suggestions in detail on Pages X-X of this response letter.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:36:RESPONSE: We have addressed these points by making changes to the Introduction (pp. X) and General Discussion (pp. X). We discuss the long-term global support for corporate DEI and avoid referring to any ΓÇ£timestampedΓÇ¥ trends.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:37:We have also sought to clarify the high-level conditions under which we expect our theory to hold. In the revised manuscript, we acknowledge that firmsΓÇÖ pullbacks from explicit DEI commitments may reduce one source of external pressure on decision-makers to avoid patterns of selections that might be judged as signaling prejudice. At the same time, we explain how organizational commitments are not the only reason people would be expected to care about feedback on the low rates of race/gender diversity in  their past selectees. Anti-discrimination law, the visibility of selection decisions, employee and stakeholder expectations, broader reputational concerns, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments should all continue to make race and gender consequential in selection contexts even if a specific employer is not supportive of DEI policies. We now state more clearly that descriptive feedback should be most likely to matter when past selection patterns could raise concerns about prejudice, and less likely to matter in environments where those concerns are less likely to arise. Given your note that an additional study is not required, in order to be maximally responsive to your earlier comment about streamlining the manuscript, we address this issue through writing. Our point-by-point reply to Reviewer 2 (Page X of this response letter) dives into this more deeply, and our General Discussion now identifies exploring whether organizational DEI climate may moderate the effect of feedback about race/gender on subsequent selection decisions as a valuable direction for future research.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:39:RESPONSE: We thank you for this feedback and agree that the prior versionΓÇÖs repeated presentation of the same comparisons made the empirical sections longer than warranted. The revised manuscript is now [X] pages and reflects a substantial streamlining of the Methods and Results sections, particularly for later studies to avoid unnecessary repetition/redundancy. To that end, and following your guidance, we have relegated the reporting of the regression specifications behind the secondary feedback-about-race/gender-versus-other-attribute comparisons to a dedicated section of the Appendix, with explicit references from the later Results sections. 
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:41:RESPONSE: Thank you for this suggestion. We ran the post-test you proposed and have incorporated the results into the Methods section of Study 1 (p. X). In a new pre-registered study (https://aspredicted.org/xa7u94.pdf), we recruited 300 Prolific participants and randomly assigned each to rate the importance of one of the four attributes featured in Study 1 (how many of the selected experts were women, worked at a university, were under 50 years old, or were based on the West Coast of the United States) for selecting NPR experts on a scale from 1 = ΓÇ£Not at all importantΓÇ¥ to 7 = ΓÇ£Very important.ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£Worked at a universityΓÇ¥ was rated as significantly more important than gender (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥: M = 3.87, SD = 1.92; ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥: M = 4.50, SD = 1.48; t(139.0) = 2.26, p = .026, d = 0.37). ΓÇ£Were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ did not differ significantly from gender in rated importance (M = 4.05, SD = 1.74; t(146.6) = 0.62, p = .534, d = 0.10). ΓÇ£Were based on the West Coast of the United StatesΓÇ¥ was rated as less important than gender (M = 3.11, SD = 1.81; t(146.7) = 2.48, p = .014, d = 0.41). Two of the three comparison attributes were thus rated as at least as important as gender. These results suggest that differences in the perceived importance of the type of feedback participants receive about their selections in Study 1 are unlikely to account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:43:RESPONSE: Thank you for raising this possibility. We now both discuss it (see p. X) and a follow-up analysis that attempts to address this point. 
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:44:We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback suggesting that women and minorities have been vastly underrepresented in their past selections compared to the U.S. population. If underrepresentation of any group is responsible for our effects, then if the descriptive feedback we provided on some other selection attribute (say, the age of prior selectees) suggested a massive underrepresentation (say, of people over 50), this might drive a similar reaction. We conducted an additional analysis to try to address this possibility. Assuming that selecting zero options with a given attribute would always signal underrepresentation, we test the hypothesis that feedback shifts in who is subsequently selected to make up for underrepresentation not just when it comes to race and gender but on any dimension. To examine this hypothesis, we pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (clustering standard errors by participant). We only retain observations involving participants who made an initial set of selections that included zero books or movies with a given attribute (e.g., a set of films in Study 3A that included zero films released after 2010, or a set of books in Study 4B that included zero books with women authors). We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, across these studies, receiving this feedback (that they had selected no women or racial minorities) significantly increases the probability of selecting a racial minority or woman as their final selection, respectively, by 22.50 percentage points (p < .001, N = 864). Among participants who initially selected zero movies, books, or authors with any of the other attributes under study (e.g., budget, year of release, or protagonistΓÇÖs profession), feedback informing them that none of their selectees had those other attributes did not significantly alter their probability of subsequently selecting an additional movie, book, or author with the relevant attribute (b = 7.25 percentage points; p = .19, N = 414). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients confirms that the pooled effect of feedback on subsequent choices is significantly larger when feedback is about the race or gender of initial selections than when it is about other features of initial selections (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.87, +27.63]). We have added a footnote to the General Discussion (p. X), anchored on the sentence where we first state the differential effect of race or gender feedback versus comparison-attribute feedback. The footnote summarizes the cross-study rule-out and points readers to Appendix Section S[X] for the full per-cell analysis. We hope these additional analyses sufficiently address your comment.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:62:More importantly, we have also expanded the theoretical framing (pp. X-X) to discuss how the classical feedback literature establishes that pairing feedback with an explicit goal works, but consistent with the broader logic of this literature, feedback regulates behavior only when there is a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. Our argument is that descriptive feedback can also be effective in domains where a strong implicit standard is already entrenched, such that no explicit goal need be paired alongside the feedback to make it useful. More specifically, we discuss how feedback evoking the past treatment of women and racial minorities provides a clean test of this theory. We propose that anti-discrimination law, social and reputational pressures to behave in ways that are not prejudicial, and selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian self-image can jointly sustain an entrenched injunctive norm against prejudiced selection (Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; ├ülvarez-Benjumea, 2023). When descriptive feedback reveals a discrepancy between this implicit standard and past behavior, we theorize that a motivation to respond without prejudice is activated even in the absence of a specific external goal. 
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:71:RESPONSE: Thank you for this valuable comment and for urging us to highlight the broader contributions of our research that go beyond any particular current state of affairs. We have updated the Introduction (pp. X) and the Discussion to try to avoid the issue that our paper could read as ΓÇ£timestampedΓÇ¥: either in the current era in which there has been backlash against DEI (which may or may not endure), or in the 2020-2024 era of massively increased support for DEI in the United States.
[codex] response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:78:We share your view that there are already quite a lot of studies in this paper. Rather than adding another, we have sought to engage with the important issues you raise narratively (this also aligns with the DEΓÇÖs guidance to prioritize streamlining the manuscript).  Specifically, we have sought to sharpen our discussion of our theoretical contribution in the revised General Discussion (pp. X), building on the scope-condition discussion already present in the Future Directions and Limitations section.
