[codex] manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:43:Prior to data collection, we ran a pre-registered pretest (https://aspredicted.org/xa7u94.pdf; N = 300 Prolific participants) to compare the rated importance of the four attributes featured in Study 1 for selecting NPR experts. Each participant was randomly assigned to rate one attribute on a scale from 1 (ΓÇ£Not at all importantΓÇ¥) to 7 (ΓÇ£Very importantΓÇ¥). Compared to gender (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥: M = 3.87, SD = 1.92, n = 75), participants rated ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ as significantly more important (M = 4.50, SD = 1.48, n = 74; t(139.0) = 2.26, p = .026, d = 0.37) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ as similarly important (M = 4.05, SD = 1.74, n = 75; t(146.6) = 0.62, p = .534, d = 0.10). ΓÇ£Were based on the West Coast of the United StatesΓÇ¥ was rated as less important than gender (M = 3.11, SD = 1.81, n = 74; t(146.7) = 2.48, p = .014, d = 0.41; full results in Appendix Section S[X]). Two of the three comparison attributes were thus rated as at least as important as gender. These results suggest that differences in the perceived importance of the type of feedback participants receive about their selections in Study 1 are unlikely to account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections.
[codex] manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:92:On average, 17.5% of participantsΓÇÖ initially selected films featured female protagonists, with balance across conditions (p = 0.813; see Appendix Table/Section X). As shown in Figure S2B and in our primary, pre-registered OLS regression (Model 1 of Table S5), participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a woman protagonist as their seventh and final film in the gender feedback condition (40.64% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist) than in the no gender feedback condition (20.08% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist; B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], t(998) = 7.24, p < .001, see Table S5 Model 1). These results were robust to several alternative specifications, including controlling for participant gender, race, and age, and analyzing our data with logistic regression (see Appendix Table S6 for robustness checks). In addition, as shown in Figure S2B and Table S5 (Models 5-8), and as predicted, the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a 7th film with a woman protagonist was larger than the effect of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of initial films selected with a (1) budget above $40M (F(1, 1992) = 65.06, p < .001), (2) political leader protagonist (F(1, 1992) = 57.74, p < .001), or (3) release year after 2010 (F(1, 1992) = 12.44, p < .001) on subsequent selections of a 7th and final biopic with, respectively, a (1) budget above $40M, (2) political leader protagonist, or (3) release year after 2010 (in fact, all other types of feedback had insignificant effects on subsequent film selections).
[codex] manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:148:Procedure. Following a similar procedure to Studies 2ΓÇô4 participants imagined  planning a major international business conference and selecting a panel of six business leaders (from a list of 25 real leaders in randomized order) to provide insights into the global business landscape.We included each leaderΓÇÖs name (e.g., Jeff Bezos, Mary Barra), title (e.g., Founder, CEO), and company affiliation (e.g., Amazon, General Motors). After making their initial six-person panel, participants were randomly assigned to one of four conditions in a 2 (gender feedback vs. no gender feedback) X 2 (women underrepresented vs. women overrepresented) design. Participants randomly assigned to the women underrepresented conditions made selections from a panelist candidate list including 18 men and 6 women (25% women). In the women overrepresented conditions, participants made selections from a panelist candidate list including 18 women and 6 men (75% women). Participants in the no gender feedback conditions were randomly assigned to receive separate summary statistics about both the percentage of panelists they initially selected who were (1) in the tech industry and (2) company founders. In the gender feedback conditions, participants received feedback about the percentage of panelists they had selected who were women as well as the two summary statistics about past selectees that were provided to participants in the no gender feedback condition. We ensured balance in the fraction of men and women candidates who were in the tech industry and company founders across the women underrepresented and women overrepresented conditions. After receiving feedback, participants selected a seventh and final panelist from the original set, and their prior selections were highlighted.
